### File Format Requirements

Every TreeDB-owned file format should define:

```text
magic header
format version
record encoding
checksum strategy
append/replace behavior
compaction behavior
crash recovery behavior
upgrade/migration behavior
human-debug dump tooling
```

MVP implementation rules:

* Use atomic rename for compacted catalog replacement.
* Use append-only writes for audit and operation logs.
* Use segment files for graph and search indexes.
* Use manifest swaps for graph/search snapshot updates.
* Use Git refs/objects as the source of truth for repository content.
* Use registry manifests for repository placement and federation state.
* Use configurable fsync policy.
* Run recovery scanning on startup.
* Keep a simple `treedb doctor` or equivalent diagnostic target in scope.

## Gitoxide/Git Implementation Policy

TreeDB should use Rust/Gitoxide (`gix`) as the primary Git implementation wherever practical.

The `treedb_git` crate owns ordinary Git operations:

```text
open repository
initialize/import repository
inspect remotes
inspect refs
resolve branch/tag/commit
read tree entries
read blob content
write blob/tree changes
compute status
compute diffs
create commits
fetch refs/objects for mirror sync
push refs/objects where explicitly allowed
manage worktree/materialized workspace state where supported
```

Shell `git` is allowed only as a compatibility fallback when a required operation is not yet supported by the TreeDB Gitoxide layer.

Every fallback must be:

```text
documented
feature-gated
audited
covered by a test that explains why fallback is needed
tracked as a removal candidate
```

All Git operations, whether Rust-native or fallback, should emit a normalized operation record:

```text
operation name
arguments summary
repository/workspace
node_id
result status
elapsed time
actor/session/effective scope
changed paths
commit SHA when applicable
sanitized audit payload
```

Do not log secrets or full file content by default.

## Rust/Elixir Boundary

Elixir/Phoenix should own supervision, API routing, authentication, authorization, sessions, eventing, federation orchestration, and sandbox lifecycle.

Rust should own deterministic storage and compute:

```text
treedb_store
  native file formats
  catalog read/write
  policy mirror read/write
  federation registry read/write
  placement and mirror manifests
  append logs
  segment read/write
  manifests
  recovery
  compaction

treedb_git
  Gitoxide/gix repository operations
  remote/ref inspection
  fetch/push where supported
  tree/blob reads
  diffs
  commits
  workspace/materialization helpers

treedb_graph
  Markdown/MDX/text parsing
  graph index construction
  search/ranking
  authorization-aware segment reads
  cross-repo edge segment support
  changed-path graph impact
  context construction
```

Use Rust NIFs only for bounded operations. For long-running operations, prefer Elixir-supervised Rust workers or external helper processes with a narrow protocol. Do not run arbitrary shell commands inside Rust NIFs.

