## Final MVP Definition

TreeDB MVP is complete when:

1. TreeDB runs canonically as a containerized service with Dockerfile and Docker Compose support.
2. Development supports hot reload without host Erlang/Elixir/Rust/Node toolchain installation.
3. Large Git repositories can remain on TreeDB volumes.
4. TreeDB-owned state lives in a TreeDB-native data directory, not PostgreSQL or SQLite.
5. The TreeDB data directory is mounted explicitly as `/var/lib/treedb` in the container and holds local repository copies.
6. Ordinary Git repository reads and commits use Gitoxide/gix wherever practical.
7. Authentication and repo/path/ref access are enforced for all operations.
8. A stateless worker can update repository files through the TypeScript SDK without cloning the repository.
9. TreeDB creates a Git commit with changed paths and audit events.
10. Agents can explore repositories through structured file/search APIs.
11. Agents can run constrained remote shell commands when necessary.
12. TreeDB can build a basic graph index and context output for text and Markdown/MDX content.
13. TreeDB supports single-repository queries in MVP and has API/storage shapes ready for future federation-aware cross-repository queries.
14. TreeDB includes node identity, repository placement, mirror records, and migration records as first-class storage/API foundations.
15. SDK local mode and TreeDB remote mode can both pass integration tests against the same generic repository fixture.
16. TreeDB can restart and recover repository catalog, policy records, placement records, workspace state, audit logs, graph manifests, and snapshot manifests from its own data directory.
17. TreeDB remains a Git/repository database: higher-level concepts are added by SDK/core/control-plane layers, not embedded in TreeDB.

